The three `// gc1-allow:` comments are placed as the first line inside the factory body, not on the `jest.mock(` call line as CLAUDE.md requires. Affects lines 9, 16, and 23. If the GC1 lint rule uses a per-line regex these annotations will not be detected, leaving the mocks silently unprotected for future runs.

Move each annotation to the `jest.mock(` call line itself:

```
// Before:
jest.mock(MODULE_PATH, () => ({
  // gc1-allow: barrel exports RN components ...

// After:
jest.mock(MODULE_PATH, () => ({ // gc1-allow: barrel exports RN components ...
```

---

**File:** `apps/mobile/src/components/session/use-session-streaming.ts`, `continueWithMessage`

The `while (activeContinueRef.current) { await activeContinueRef.current; }` pattern serializes two concurrent callers correctly (B waits for A). With three callers, B and C both await the same promise. When A resolves and sets `activeContinueRef.current = null`, B and C both exit the loop in the same microtask tick — before either one has set the ref to its own `currentTurn`. Both then set `activeContinueRef.current` independently, one overwrites the other's promise, and they proceed concurrently.

In practice the streaming guard (`isStreaming = true` disables the send button) prevents user-driven N>=3 overlaps. The risk is in programmatic paths: auto-retry, replay-on-idempotency-key, homework OCR queued sends. A safer pattern chains promises through the ref instead of polling it:

```ts
const prev = activeContinueRef.current ?? Promise.resolve();
let resolveCurrentTurn!: () => void;
const currentTurn = new Promise<void>((r) => { resolveCurrentTurn = r; });
activeContinueRef.current = prev.then(() => currentTurn);
await prev; // wait only for the direct predecessor
```

This guarantees each waiter enters exactly once, in arrival order, regardless of how many stack up simultaneously.

